I played Lara Croft GO they did before this and it was pretty good. This 
has some of that feel to it, but lacks the overall complexity (ie, no 
vertical dimensions, no objects you have to move as part of the strategy, 
etc.). It held my interest long enough to finish it, which took me a few 
days. But given its lack of complexity, they should have added a LOT more 
levels. Also annoying that you have to figure out what the different 
weapons/tools are on your own. I saw someone else use the term 'rushed to 
market' in their review, and I got that feeling too. Character dialogue was 
very sophomoric and poorly written. Basically I am a big fan of the Room 
games and constantly searching for something as entrenching and 
intellectually challenging - this definitely wasn't it, but if you are 
looking for a game that will keep you occupied when you're bored , this 
does an ok job

If Google allowed for half-stars, I would have given it a 4.5. It is a solid game with nice graphics and very good puzzles. Many of them had me scratching my head for quite a few a few minutes. As a Deus Ex fan, I thought the music and environments were spot on, and I loved the addition of hacking terminals and using augmentations to solve puzzles. Unfortunately, I played this after finishing Lara Croft Go, which shows what Square Enix is capable of, but didn't achieve in Deus Ex Go.   I truly enjoyed the game, but the "story" was half-hearted, the ending was non-consequential (despite the name), and I didn't feel engaged with Jensen the way I did with Lara. I was particularly disappointed that an effort was made to force a choice at the end, but it literally made ZERO difference how you completed the level. Also, the enemies were much less complex, which wasn't made up for with the augs and hacking. There was no equivalent of the salamanders or snakes, for instance. I would still rate this game well, because it was definitely worth the price of entry, but it's not the best in the series.

For a series about multiple paths towards accomplishing its objectives, it's disappointing to see that the puzzles are constrained to only one solution.   The simple gameplay and graphics end up being fine, but the controls are finicky at times and can lead to accidental deaths, which can get frustrating. If you dislike trial and error gameplay it's not for you, but for those who like Deus Ex, puzzle games, and some light story there is some enjoyment that can be found here, and it is worth the current sale price of 99 cents.

In fact it's a step back. I hated the step limitations of Hitman Go and found the goals too repetitive and arbitrar. Lara Go focused much more on great diverse puzzles and discovery. Deus Ex yet again introduces stupid step limits and "boring" level mechanics in concise environments. Is this game challenging? I believe that designing a difficult puzzle can be challenging, but the campaign is just a tutorial. What makes a puzzle difficult is variables. The campaign only introduces ideas and new mechanics, but other than that its very straight forward. I hope this answers a few questions and helps others design challenging puzzles.

Thoroughly enjoyable GO game. I bought all three in the recent %-off deal and played a couple of levels of each to get a feel for them. This was the first one I chose to complete, I guess because the narrative, although fairly minimalist, hooked me in. The puzzles quickly ramp up to being an enjoyable challenge; solutions can be bought , in-game, although purists (like me) might consider this cheating :=). The music and sound effects are superb, adding to the immersion. One plus for fans of replay value, you get additional sets of puzzles to try from the community as well as being able to design your own, so even though puzzle games perhaps don't intrinsically have the replay value of other genres, you can keep on defeating Jensen's enemies in this game after completing the actual main "mission", if you want to. All in all, a worthy addition to your collection if you're a fan of puzzlers. And I say all this having never spent a second playing any other Deus Ex game. I came for the puzzle experience and was absolutely not disappointed.

I just finished the game so have full experience to comment. I am a big fan of the Go series, and hold Hitman Go as a benchmark for mobile gaming. Tomb Raider Go was fun, but failed to hold up to the same level of quality (sadly since I am a big Tomb Raider fan).  Deus Ex Go is sort of in the middle ground. I still think Hitman was far superior. However, that being said Deus Ex is still amazing. It captures the feeling of the franchise very well, and this is the first time they have attempted a full narrative / storyline with a Go game. They did a good job. Critiquing it, I think the first half of the game is far too easy. I didn't really get challenged until after that point. But then it gets interesting, and the trial and error seeing how all the various parts interact gets really fun. There's not a lot, but at the same time they max out what there is.  My only other critique is that it sucks battery fast, and sometimes (but not all) my Nexus 6 got really hot from playing it.

A fun new iteration in a consistently enjoyable series. It nicely continues the GO gameplay style while mixing it up with new elements that fit in the larger world of Deus Ex.   I especially love the visuals. Excellent choices on what effects to prioritize to make it look good while keeping the performance reasonable. I'm particularly impressed with how good it looks with vertex colors, rather than textures, on most of the materials. ;)  My only complaint is that I wish the story scenes had more than just static character images (ie. changing expressions, maybe fake movement via 2D skeletal animation, etc). I know it's nitpicking, but it's the one thing that really feels lacking in the visuals department. :(

Loved the game but refunded. This is purely because I bought the game because of a promotional email I received. Here it states you can earn free Praxis kits for the forthcoming Deus Ex Mankind Divided game. I have that pre-ordered for the PS4. However nowhere in the promotional email does it mention that it doesn't apply to PS4. It's this deception that warrants a refund. It's a matter of principal. I'll wait for the price to drop as there is no incentive to play right now for a PS4 owner.
